A data collection form was prepared using the Joanna Briggs Institute (JBI) manual for conducting systematic reviews of intervention studies. The form consists of study characteristics such as author, year, country, design, sample size, inclusion criteria, and exclusion criteria; participant details such as age and sex; randomization;

PubMed search strategy Serial number Themes Keywords and combinations Search results 1 Mobile related mobile* OR phone* OR "mobile phone" OR "cell phone" OR "cell phones" OR "smart phone" OR "smartphones" OR tele-medicine OR telemedicine OR "mobile health" OR "mHealth" OR telehealth OR eHealth OR mHealth OR telemetry OR telephone 267,649 2 Message related message* OR messages OR "text messaging" OR "text-based messages" OR "text messages" OR "text messaged" OR voice OR "voice message" OR "voice messages" OR "short message service" OR "short message" OR sms OR SMS OR text* OR txt OR texts OR texting OR eHealth OR internet OR email 511,372 3 Weight related weight* OR "weight loss" OR "weight management" OR "weight reduction" OR overweight OR obesity OR obese OR adiposity OR "body fat" OR "body weight" OR Anthropometry OR "Body Mass Index" OR BMI OR waist OR "waist circumference" OR "Waist-Hip Ratio" OR "Body Fat Distribution" OR "obesity management" OR "skinfold" OR "overweight therapy" OR "obesity therapy" OR (weight AND [loss OR manage* OR maintenance OR maintain OR maintain*]) OR (weight AND [intervention* OR program*]) OR (weight AND [fitness OR physical activity OR physical exercise OR diet* OR nutrition]) 1,825,046 4 Combination of themes #1 AND #2 AND #3 and with search limit only to English literature 3727 controls; intervention characteristics such as types, durations, contents, tailoring, measurements, attritions, behavior change options, behavior change techniques, and theories; and other additional relevant study findings.

The data extraction was piloted on the included studies and refined accordingly. One author (TA) has extracted relevant information from the included studies, and a second reviewer then extracted one fourth of included studies (four articles) and cross-matched for consistency and accuracy. However, there was no significant difference found in extracted data sets for both reviewers.
